Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked jeopardizing the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an additional one hundred crowns monthly for housing.
Households will have to pay extra from January not only for all types of energy but also for water and sewerage, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will therefore have to draw from their wallets up to a hundred crowns monthly more from January than they do now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more. dear.
The increase in electricity should be around 100 crowns annually more for apartment households than at present.
However, all suppliers have reduced electricity prices given the significant development to encourage the manufacture of renewable energies, in particular photovoltaic batteries.
The gas increases moderately but of course when people need it the most for heating and therefore have the greatest consumption.
We can therefore also count a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the larger municipalities that are planning the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 crowns more per month, families in Libérec will pay more than 1000 crowns annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sewerage in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change Praguers will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison to the whole country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sewerage increases by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will increase, for example, significantly in the 450,000 apartments for rent from January, ie at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2,500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided on an increase of up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be taken to court by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could rise next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whiskey are stolen from parents.
These are the drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for a recurrence are no exception.
This results from the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to admissions in children&#39;s departments of hospitals.
&quot;Beers or wines are out of fashion because it takes time to get drunk.&quot;
“The trend is really towards hard liquor,” said Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children&#39;s department at Horovice hospital in central Bohemia.
&quot;When they manage to steal a daddy&#39;s bottle from the cupboard, it&#39;s sometimes whisky, but it&#39;s fernet and vodka that prevail.&quot;
&quot;Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it&quot;, explains the Head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokesperson for the Motol hospital, also agrees with him.
&quot;In general, it&#39;s rum or fernet&quot;.
&quot;It is the fashionable alcohol today, especially in elementary schools&quot;.
“In some cases it was slivovice that they brought from home,” Jurinova added.
According to Department Head Pélikan, seeing drunken children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen on hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice last year, he was in Motol where he practiced for ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wider surroundings completely drunk.
&quot;A young girl was hospitalized like this four times
&quot;She began her career at twelve years old when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand of alcohol in her blood plus a mixture with ecstasy&quot;, described the doctor in this particularly important case.
&quot;She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Center at a party&quot;.
&quot;What is interesting is that it did not appear strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours,&quot; said the Director of the Department, astonished.
It is precisely the disinterestedness of the parents or their extraordinary tolerance in the face of the fact that their offspring are addicted to drink which are the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, we are not talking about dependency, in its strict sense, for children.
“Under the term alcoholic we mean a chronic alcohol dependence lasting several years with all the phenomena that result from it but which are not found in children”.
&quot;Among those who use alcohol repeatedly, it is more a question of a significantly unfavorable socio-family background&quot;, explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunken children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe poisoning requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are taken home after emergency treatment by parents or by the police are not counted.
Besides the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pélikan there are three seasonal waves to be reckoned with: Witches&#39; Day, New Year&#39;s Eve and the end of the school year. .
&quot;Either they drink out of spite after bad results or, on the contrary, they celebrate the start of the holidays&quot;.
“Of course I experienced on the day of the witches an admission of 7 drunken children at once”, underlined Pélikan.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from a &quot;hangover&quot;.
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated with an infusion of glucose and nutrients the body needs.
&quot;They are better off for that since they spend a great evening then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them&quot;.
“They are only surprised at where they are,” adds Pélikan, knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients, at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Transport by ambulance and hospitalization on an intensive care bed can cost up to tens of thousands of crowns.
&quot;From time to time, I applied this as a means of education by counting to these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to reimburse a single evening&quot;, added Pélikan.
However, according to him, the health insurance companies in their management in regression, which should recover from the parents the expenses related to the care, do not treat the cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two L-159 planes of the five in all, against which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport planes, took off on Tuesday for Seville in Spain, where the Casa-EADS aircraft manufacturer is based.
This is the first time that devices of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
They have, however, been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 which have been in service with the Czech army until now and which were airworthy.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defence, the physical departure of the planes from Vodochody is currently unknown.
&#39;The single-seat L-159 aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from long-stored aircraft without causing additional burdens or investments for the Ministry of Defence&#39;.
&quot;The L-159 T1 two-seaters were exchanged in the state&quot;, declared for Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not be without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
