Index finger longer than ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men whose index finger is longer than their ring finger are at a lower risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
It may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
&quot;Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men before age 60,&quot; said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for cancer research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should get tested for prostate cancer, especially when combined with genetic risk or other aggravating factors like family health history, Eeles added.
During the period of 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had their right hand index finger shorter than their ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men under 60 the reduction in risk reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two cited fingers - formed during the prenatal period - in particular indicates different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
A less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him that the relationship between length fingers and cancer is &quot;fully proven&quot;.
