However, Luciano does not forget during training the icing on the cake of the national superstructure and, in general, of the south: &quot;Italian gelato is simply the best: and then it still retains a hell of a dose of romanticism.&quot;
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees using an electronic program, then cools immediately to four degrees.
He then opens a tap installed on the machine: a pasteurized basic white cream emerges, the foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately assailed with questions: Is it possible to make ice cream using only natural substances without stabilizer?
How can we give free rein to the personal pleasure of experimentation?
Mr. Luciano cautions against being misled by the spirit of the times.
Anyone who only speaks of ice cream &quot;made from natural ingredients&quot; may have used stabilizers despite this: most often a natural product, for example guar seed flour obtained from the guar bean.
It is obviously possible to make ice cream without using stabilizer, only it must be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer will not bite anything but ice pellets.
Some modifications of the basic mass are permitted.
It becomes more exciting with the aromas.
The master Luciano establishes the difference between the ingredients that one acquires in the fruit or confectionery section of the supermarket.
In addition, there are powder and pastes.
&quot;Vendors will all try to pass you dozens of flavored ingredients.&quot;
&quot;However, you should just give it a try.&quot;
Either in fruit sorbet recipes with sugar and fresh fruit.
Either in ice creams made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs, becomes a yellow cream and constitutes, when cocoa powder is added, the base of all possible chocolate desserts.
Now all course participants must switch to using the ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla flavor or other ingredients natural.
The different kinds of fruit ice cream are also subjected to the same experiment.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purees: From a taste point of view, this is not absolutely better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily have the taste of nuts, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
The hugely popular kiwi ice cream is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
&quot;Only a balanced mixture properly enhances the taste of an ice cream,&quot; says Luciano.
Making ice cream is an exercise in calculation: if peach puree with a lot of sugar is used, the amount of sugar must be reduced in the basic recipe.
Extra sugar is needed for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents a device with which he determines the sugar content of different types of fruit (winemakers use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, tables make calculations easier.
The manufacture of ice no longer requires as much physical intervention as in the past.
It&#39;s not just the basic mace auto-making machine that helps.
There is also a device in which the available ice mixture is simultaneously beaten to make it creamy and brought back to negative temperatures.
Despite all the automations, slight breakdowns are not excluded.
Brazilian Gustavo smears head to toe in mashed fruit and splashes on his fellow students when control of the colossal mixing bowl slips away from him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that &quot;an incident like this is likely to happen in every lesson: it&#39;s only a matter of time.&quot;
