The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime has become a bigger concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarómetro survey taken from 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it tracks changes in attitude in the region.
Two related things emerge from the results of this year&#39;s survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is Latin America&#39;s fairly sunny mood.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific Rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy has rebounded after suffering a sharp drop in output last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are staunch Democrats, pushing down the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way their country&#39;s democracy worked in practice; this is the same figure as last year but with a strong increase on the 25% in 2001 (graph 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in their country&#39;s parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but up sharply compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
A decade ago, economic problems in Latin America shook support for democracy.
If this held up during the global financial crisis, it is certainly because many of the countries of America suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a social safety net helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year, to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see graph 4).
Brazil&#39;s strong economic performance and the popularity of its incumbent president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has increased.
It was only the second time since the poll began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue for their country (see Table 5 ).
About 31% say they or someone close to them has been the victim of a crime in the past year; nevertheless, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
Stronger economic performance is reflected in rising support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 ( see graph 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel this way (and 80% support private enterprise); even if their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the biggest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year)
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
