tiptoe to the center
Weeks after being suddenly widowed, Cristina Fernández, President of Argentina, enjoyed a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rating by 20 points, to more than 50%; this is her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Yet turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could hinge on whether the visibly grieving Ms Fernández chooses whether or not to abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, on this subject, the signs remain confused.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had a history of crafting budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Ms. Fernández&#39;s government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation descended into disarray following the death of Mr Kirchner from a heart attack on October 27.
Some of the dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement rallied behind Ms. Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (where a parliamentarian punched one of his peers in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress failed to approve the 2011 budget.
&quot;I&#39;m not going to argue,&quot; the president said.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president even greater leeway to spend at will.
The economy is largely overheating: it is likely to grow by almost 9% this year.
The official rate of inflation now stands at 11.1% but many private estimates and union wage demands see the figure close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to deal with the IMF, he harassed the private sector and purged INDEC, the statistical office, which falsified official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs Fernández now moderate these policies?
She called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And its officials say they want to limit salary increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by high world prices for Argentina&#39;s agricultural exports.
But inflation eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
This may be why Ms. Fernández shows signs of wanting to restore Argentina&#39;s financial relations with the rest of the world.
This year, the government struck a deal with bondholders who had refused an earlier forced debt restructuring that Argentina failed to meet in 2001.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the economy minister, announced that the Fund would provide &quot;technical assistance&quot; to design a new national consumer price index; which looks like a prelude to the cleanup of INDEC.
It is unclear whether Ms Fernández wants to stay in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer by her side.
If she does, she needs to gain support from the middle class, among whom Kirchnerism is highly advocated.
By the time the Argentinians return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have ebbed.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of her husband&#39;s policies.
