An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, widens the field for finding new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although the researchers discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
&quot;This organism has a double capacity.&quot;
&quot;It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic.&quot;
&quot;That&#39;s why it&#39;s very special, even if it&#39;s far from a truly &#39;alien&#39; life form,&quot; commented Paul Davies CW of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday&#39;s online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue growing after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
&quot;One wonders what&#39;s still possible,&quot; said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important when it comes to the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not release details of the find, generated widespread speculation on the internet that the report may leak the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It was not the case.
The discovery &quot;shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms might be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that the &#39;standard&#39; set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed,&quot; commented Charles Cockell, Professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Science Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the search party.
&quot;This work is novel because it shows the substitution of one element for another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure,&quot; Cockell added.
It was no accidental discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to substitute one for the other.
&quot;Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.&quot;
&quot;As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately.&quot;
&quot;But arsenic is different enough that it doesn&#39;t work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and kind of erases the work of our biochemical machinery,&quot; Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows best on phosphorus but the fact that it can live on arsenic instead raises the possibility that an arsenic-using life form may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
Arsenic was more common early in Earth&#39;s existence, she says; thus, researchers have speculated that early life forms might have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways life formed, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning,&quot; said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe&#39;s research team. -Simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
