Can civility bridge the divides?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a modicum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday&#39;s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the &quot;lame duck&quot; session.
But clearly there was at least a polite discussion of the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points. Supporter point scoring blank.
Wednesday&#39;s open meeting of the President&#39;s Deficit Committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
It&#39;s barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That&#39;s why Tuesday&#39;s meeting and subsequent comments from attendees exposed minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it&#39;s taxes, expenses, health care or rights, the two parties remain miles apart.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
&quot;There&#39;s no doubt things have changed in tone,&quot; said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now with the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
&quot;It&#39;s inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade.
It&#39;s good.&quot;
On some issues, including those on the agenda for the &quot;lame duck&quot; session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday&#39;s meeting at the White House, more optimism hangs over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the &quot;lame duck&quot;, with the ratification of the &quot;New START&quot; pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the &quot;lame duck&quot; session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, the psychology in the short term will go back to one of confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
&quot;I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 pre-show or shadow-boxing to the main event of 2012,&quot; he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea party who helped create it.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the deficit committee&#39;s recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending. .
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and have, they say, pushed the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the chosen ones of the group; suggesting that on tax issues, at least today, there is little incentive or willingness to compromise.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and health care; only to be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both sides will watch the public reaction carefully.
Whoever will be judged at a loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic view nonetheless.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there appears to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was. then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as just a prelude to a more consequential election in 2012.
Given that reality, the civility on display this week might be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort from both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
