Red Bull triumphs in F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
Software creates improvements on cars in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select world of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into account the options of a new team that had just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the last phase of the championship they all bet on the triumph of Fernando Alonso&#39;s Ferrari.
Without diminishing the skill as a driver of the champion, the German Sebastien Vette, nor the capacity of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the world of Formula 1 we speak of the legend of the &quot;secret weapon&quot; that the company multinational Siemens has put at the hands of Red Bull to turn it into a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with objectives far removed from the high motoring competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computing instrument has been used to create assembly lines of manufacturing factories all over the world, energy stations, high precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or the process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding defects and avoidable costs.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi planes or Nissan&#39;s most famous utility vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory has enabled Red Bull to create and execute &quot;in a few hours, almost in real time&quot;, the modifications, changes and improvements detected during races and tests.
Russwurm explains that the 1992 teams had an average of 10 technicians on their teams who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four vehicle upgrades each season.
The Red Bull team currently employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull cars except the engine, which is Renault&#39;s exclusive responsibility.
We modify the materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements.
Changes can go from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation of this madness of technological perfection is the amount of 40 million dollars that each Formula 1 team can spend as a limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to create and produce its cars in a locality 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that happens there is considered &quot;top secret&quot;.
The staff for this duty numbers 580 people, including two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull&#39;s Formula 1 hero, arguably, is recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Between the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other hidden protagonists, whose activity is invaluable and whose notoriety is nil.
Factory technology director Steve Nevey says five years ago you could argue that R+D advances in racing cars brought 50% of the wins and the drivers were responsible for the rest. .
Today these percentages have changed and the technology represents the 85% of the success, while the pilots bring the 15% of the added value.
Nevey admits that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by IT, because &quot;they are unpredictable gladiators&quot;.
