Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin opted to stay in the euro, but it set the conditions for the whole Union.
Market tensions provoked a dual government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has announced new methods of adjustment, which vary from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private employment agencies or the abolition of the 426 euro aid for unemployed without professional contribution to the privatization of the 49% of AENA, management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins the criticisms of Chancellor Angela Merkel regarding her responsibility to untie the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel&#39;s position is not an error in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another restriction of the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, in Germany people are beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macro-economic control, budgetary rigor, fines for countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has long been defined, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first signal of divergence between what Germany thought we should do (fiscal austerity plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second blow to the Central European country was when Merkel hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
From then on it was the object of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, asking for the reform of the treaties of the Union to make possible the rescue of a country and at the same time oblige the private lenders to support a part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although a little watered down, was approved and, in the following months, we should witness the process of reform of the Union that will make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And she tells us all that, even if now we have to take measures with which we may not really agree, from that date the old functioning of the euro would have ended .
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries which break the rules will be severely sanctioned, they may be forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will also bear part of the costs.
Germany signals to us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high rates of savings and investment, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as that which presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be bad not to hear it.
It is not only a question of renewing the public deficit at 3% in 2013.
What is asked of us is much harder.
And what he must absolutely not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil brings greater tranquility to us.
And that we know how to seize the opportunity we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday&#39;s meeting with big business and yesterday&#39;s announcement of the new measures) suggests that, despite criticism from Merkel, we paved the way for the thesis that we must put our house in order.
But the red line Germany has drawn is there, and they don&#39;t seem to be moving it.
And among the possibilities that we are considering, we cannot exclude that of abandoning a monetary zone that is too full of unserious countries.
And in this case, Germany will always be able to tell us that she warned us.
Sport and Fraud of the Law
Tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape punishment.
The expulsion planned in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused much ink to flow on the unsportsmanlike nature of such behavior and whether both players are expected to be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before ending the match (which their team already clearly won), the two players deliberately wasted time when they committed fouls to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will end up being leaders of their group, the two players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the play-off against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards to the next phase.
Eventually, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned the team&#39;s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and various economic sums to the players involved.
The invocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new, if not rather common practice in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of the sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team from the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which in past occasions has condemned to a fine its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to his dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks if this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of the sport, that is to say, if with these actions one commits a fraud of law; because, indeed, they are respectful actions with the sporting regulations, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to sportsmanship.
One of the assets that includes the sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, that is to say there has been no play violent.
Another of those benefits that are alluded to with correct play is to prevent the offending team from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating o fraud of the law, since its violation of the rules has not been carried out. in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty from the referee.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is the type of advantage that offenders obtain from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put the rival at a disadvantage and neither does one obtain an advantage in the same match, because obviously the result of the action supposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that&#39;s not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn&#39;t rely on those players.
Obviously the advantage consists in the fact that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So that climbing the ladder is not so clear that it is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sportsmanship, which is still part of making strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (that would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they rather chose the moment in which they submitted to it .
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or running away from that one.
Even if the boundary between genius and the fraud of the law is diffuse, in this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the manner in which the headmistress conveyed to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of the sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
