China maintains greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of this country in the COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the trace of coal and detailed that it maintains its offer to reduce until 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its greenhouse gas emissions Greenhouse.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent before 2020, assured Su Wei, representative of this country at COP16.
In his first public appearance in the 16th Conference of the Parties of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the trace of coal and reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, over the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
Nevertheless, he made it clear that China will not change its goals, but it will continue to work together with the international community in this area.
He mentioned that China&#39;s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and pilot program support.
Progress has been made in all of these areas, including the approval last year of a new Energy Law, which recognizes the objectives being addressed with regard to the reduction of greenhouse gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, federal authorities have worked in a coordinated manner with state and local governments to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, he said, there are various multi-year plans underway or completed, both funded by the Chinese government and the governments of other countries.
For example, he mentioned, the Energy Efficiency Program, which has been implemented for the past five years and has received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private initiative.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another for the change from incandescent lamps to energy-saving lamps and another for mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
At the same table, Martin Krol, scientific advisor to the government of this country regarding climate change, assured that China&#39;s efforts have been greater than we think.
For example, he stated, the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is three tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9% of the historical contribution in the contamination.
Likewise, it has made unprecedented efforts in energy use, how to increase energy efficiency by 20 percent in the past five years and plans to do another similar one around 2020, he said.
