The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Service Centers for Visa Applicants before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost the waiting time will be reduced.
Effective January 10, 2011, visa processing procedures at US Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant&#39;s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the aspirants, among which we mention the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make one payment for getting an appointment, another payment for visa processing and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars in the case of visas with request (here includes visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for visas of traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to appear for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves at the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there for less time than before.
Likewise, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service charge of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
