Hydro-Québec awarded $450 million in contracts by mutual agreement to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts, it was a consortium made up of the firms BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor which obtained the most important, that of the management of the project, for a sum of 295 million dollars without call for tenders.
This consortium, called Énergie gérance, was formed in 2004 at the same time as Hydro-Québec chose to entrust the private sector with its responsibility for managing this major $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the Énergie gérance consortium won the lucrative contract without a public call for tenders.
For the Parti Québécois, the use of business consortia poses a serious ethical problem that risks eliminating competition and causing price increases.
&quot;It&#39;s the new way to collide and take down the competition.&quot;
&quot;That is to say that people, instead of doing it secretly, now do it openly,&quot; PQ MP Sylvain Simard said yesterday at a press conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr. Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because he says it is difficult to see how the public interest can be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, replied in the afternoon, vigorously denying that there was collusion for this contract.
&quot;I&#39;m starting to have my trip&quot;, she cursed, arguing that the PQ had been &quot;dishonest&quot; and had &quot;lack of rigor&quot;.
She said that &quot;it would be the least of things&quot; for the PQ to apologize.
The consortia formula is a common practice all over the world.
It is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to combine their respective expertise in order to respond to a call for tenders for a complex project.
The Eastmain project involves a high level of complexity given the scope of the work.
The work is in progress and should last until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition acting; there was negotiation.
Also, the consortia formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the consortia formula in the consulting engineering sector is the subject of a government investigation.
A quick overview of the Quebec enterprise register reveals more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
Thus, the Dessau firm works in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and other Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to one and the same legal person, namely Dessau.
As for the Énergie gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau pointed out that &quot;the James Bay territory responds to specific labor dynamics and that Hydro-Québec has responded to them in a particular way since the 1970s&quot;.
The big boss of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d&#39;énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), gave an explanation that raised eyebrows about the fact that the project management contract was awarded by mutual agreement.
&quot;If you go to tender and there are few bidders, your prices will be higher.&quot;
&quot;You have two choices: either you take the people who are in that market and say: we will negotiate a satisfactory agreement at a good price.&quot;
&quot;But the idea is that it&#39;s not the price that&#39;s important, it&#39;s the skill of the people,&quot; said Mr. Laporte.
This contract awarded to the Énergie gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts worth more than $50,000 obtained by the Parti Québécois.
