Another finding: half of consumers doubt the reliability of official certifications affixed to so-called fair trade products, but also the credibility of products and brands claiming to be eco-responsible, indicates the Barometer.
In the same vein, the discourse of politicians on this theme is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this segment of consumption currently driven by nearly a third of Quebec consumers.
Indeed, the emptiness and dubious nature of the information would calm the enthusiasm of 46% of consumers.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
Moreover, a third of Quebecers also say they are wary of the alleged performance of the green products or services that we are trying to put in their hands.
On another note, nearly half of consumers in 2010 changed their habits and especially changed the brand of one or more products to meet their conviction.
Up to 61%, they also favored purchases from merchants in their neighborhood and favored the purchase of food products grown in their region, indicates the Barometer.
