A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to obtaining a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction that must be achieved to stabilize the planet&#39;s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of major concrete projects that the UN hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the absence of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs which still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global emissions of GHG from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this assessment another 5 Gt to manage to stabilize by 2020 the rise in the climate at 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5% produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by two times more.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy. than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the savings possible with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have expressed reservations about compact fluorescent light bulbs since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers in place of instructions.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not CFLs, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to generate wasted electricity in incandescent light bulbs. .
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would thus save a billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, ie the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power stations, the construction of which would cost it 2.5 billion.
