Vengeful hackers and stagecoach spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that only appears as a scandal when faced with the hypocrisy that governs the relationship between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let&#39;s go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that each file compiled by a secret service (of whatever nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The &quot;extraordinary&quot; American revelations about Berlusconi&#39;s sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those owned by Berlusconi), and the grimly cartoonish profile of Gaddafi had long been for cabaret artists matter for sketches.
The rule that secret files should only consist of previously known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret service, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous works. .
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to the occult only believe in what they already know, and which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown&#39;s success.
Ditto for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, an editor at Liberation), who only accepts as true what he recognizes.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the US Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same that Newsweek published the week before.
So why have the revelations about these files caused so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since Heads of State can telephone each other or take a plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, apart from a few small exercises of representation, have been transformed into centers of espionage.
Any spectator of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only out of hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that some hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world deals a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims in crisis so much as the &quot;executioners&quot;.
But let&#39;s come to the deeper nature of what happened.
Formerly, at the time of Orwell, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction carried out, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as is happening now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the relationship of control ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen&#39;s avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold on?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said it, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is effectively an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton&#39;s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from her.
WikiLeaks did no wrong to Sarkozy or Merkel, but did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, the States will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - that would be like publishing it on a poster stuck on the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is vain to hope to be able to maintain confidential relations by telephone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and therefore fictional, but I am forced to imagine government agents moving discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable routes, in no only carrying messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing like a crab, that is to say backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has reestablished a wired (telephone) telegraph.
Videocassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now CDs (digital) only allow skipping from chapter to chapter, that is to say by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, you can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that politics and the techniques of communications should revert to horse-drawn carriages.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secrecy of the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France tweaks its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine compliance with the promises of rapidly released funding (known as fast start or early stage funding) made by developed countries.
And the big French hacks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, major side event , distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciable and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, which puts it on the right track to meet its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when we look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, &quot;new and additional&quot;, in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what &quot;new and additional&quot; means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonization, some Member States including France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, has considered 2009 as a benchmark: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or in terms of level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of &quot;all new projects&quot; for the year 2010 are &quot;new and additional&quot;.
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of France&#39;s support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment in terms of &quot;new and additional&quot; financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Here again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that we will recover as equivalent to one euro that is given... At most, only the cost of the loan for the lending country (ie the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted as part of its commitments.
But France has no use for such reasoning: it &quot;respects&quot; its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice trick!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double swindle: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to believe that it is spending 420 million &quot;new and additional&quot; in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other Member States would continue to give it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The early stage financing chapter is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to the whole climate discussion.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let&#39;s hope that won&#39;t be the case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of fast-start funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): we will not escape the question of &quot;additionality&quot; or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests with the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France&#39;s fast start and on its vision of &quot;additionality&quot; and the use of loans would be likely to increase the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
Pesticides ingested by children alert
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemical substances in one day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly Movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results &quot;have no significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with&quot;, bought between July and September the foods generally consumed in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of about ten years old, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as treats, have been examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, metals heavy and other pollutants.
The assessment of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by several institutions such as the Center international cancer research community.
&quot;Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded, we can clearly see in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to possibly carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is worrying. “, notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than ten possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, provided as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemical substances including a fungicide yet banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the ground beef, the canned tuna, and even the baguette and chewing gum were loaded with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the &quot;richest&quot; with 34 chemical residues detected and even examination of the plastic plate used to reheat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of this &quot;contaminant cocktails&quot; &quot;is probably underestimated&quot;, according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed &quot;given the urgency of the situation&quot; to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop &quot;the increase in diseases of civilization&quot;.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
